		<header>
			
			<h1>EPA negotiations compete with other priorities in ESA region</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 August 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Regional press in East Africa are reporting that ‘Europe has issued a fresh warning of possible revenue losses for Kenya should the East African Community (EAC) fail to reach a trade deal soon.’ The EC Delegate to Kenya is reported to have told Kenyan horticulture-sector stakeholders in mid June 2011 that while Burundi, Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda, as all of them are LDCs, ‘will enjoy duty-free quota access to the EU markets even if the EPA (economic partnership agreement) is not signed…. Kenya will risk seeing tariffs imposed on a good number of exports to Europe including horticulture products.’ EC representatives have expressed concern that EAC negotiators have not yet responded to ‘its latest move to relax their position over the terms that need to be met [in order] for a new trade pact with East Africa to be concluded’.</p><p>The Kenya Flower Council said in a statement that ‘growers are looking to the EU being an important destination for the Kenyan products to hasten the negotiations and provide assurance that whatever happens, Kenya, under special circumstances, will not be worse off.’</p><p>These remarks need to be seen in the context of warnings from former Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa urging ‘a more sensible approach to attain regional development goals’. Mr Mkapa raised the fundamental question ‘Does the EAC need the EPA?’, and urged a proper assessment of the costs and benefits if an EPA were signed. He noted a trend towards a declining share of the EU in the region’s exports and an increase in Africa’s share of EAC exports. He expressed particular concern about the impact of trade patterns with the EU on the structural development of the EAC economy, and also expressed fears that tariff reductions vis-à-vis the EU could undermine ‘our fragile manufacturing and agricultural sectors’, with this being compounded by restrictions on the use of traditional trade-policy tools (e.g. export taxes).</p><p>The press in the region has also noted EAC reports that the introduction of full duty-free trade within the EAC since 1 January 2010 has not had the desired trade impact. EAC Secretary-General Richard Sezibera has expressed concern that ‘there are significant and disturbing incidents of the application of non-tariff barriers as well as non-uniform application of the Common External Tariff (CET) that continue to militate against the smooth operations of the Customs Union.’ Secretary-General Sezibera warned the EAC governments of the important task ahead regarding the elimination of non-tariff barriers to trade.</p><p>This needs to be seen against the background of the introduction of various trade restrictions by EAC governments in response to emerging grain shortages (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Maize-trade-policy-decisions-highlight-need-for-closer-regional-policy-harmonisation" target="_blank">Maize trade-policy decisions highlight need for closer regional policy h...</a>’, July 2011). This has seen a situation emerge where ‘Tanzanian traders are petitioning the government to stop paying dues to the East Africa Community over Kenya's refusal to allow wheat imports from their country’. This is the culmination of nine months of lobbying from Tanzanian wheat traders, ‘who claim they are victims of unfair competition since Kenyan goods have flooded their markets’. Mohamed Bashrahil, sales and marketing manager of Azania Wheat Flour, claimed that Kenya was ‘killing the spirit of free trade in the regional bloc by not allowing flour from Tanzania into their country’.</p><p>Scheduled imports from beyond the EAC region in July are expected to ease the supply situation in Kenya, with this measure also expected to unlock hoarded stocks, thereby easing the supply constraints on maize millers. In the longer term, press reports indicate bumper maize crops in certain regions of Uganda.</p>
		
		
