				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The slow pace of progress in the EAC–EU EPA negotiations reflects the severe human and institutional resource constraints faced in least-developed country partners in following through on nominal trade-policy commitments. This limit the ability of governments to simultaneously and effectively get to grips with the implications of multiple trade-policy issues. This affects not only the conclusion of the EAC–EU EPA negotiations, but also the effective implementation of EAC policy commitments. The EAC–EU EPA issue is further complicated by the ongoing COMESA and trilateral FTA processes, where fundamental issues of policy consistency arise. These issues have already led the SADC EPA configuration to place the EPA process on hold (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/EPAs/SADC-EU-EPA-negotiations-on-hold-as-grand-FTA-challenges-become-apparent" target="_blank">SADC–EU EPA negotiations on hold as “grand FTA” challenges become apparent</a>’, July 2011).</p><p>Given that LDCs have ‘Everything But Arms’ (EBA) access to the EU market, providing market access for LDCs that is equivalent to that in the IEPA, it should come as little surprise if competing trade-policy issues are accorded a higher priority than the conclusion of the EPA negotiations by the governments of EAC LDCs.</p><p>The delays resulting from this prioritisation have led once again to the prospect being raised of Kenya losing its current preferential access to the EU market.</p>
		</div>
		
